# Architecture Rules

## Component Organization
- Shared, reusable UI primitives (Button, Input, Modal, Badge, etc.) go in `/components/ui/`
- Layout components (PageWrapper, Sidebar, Header) go in `/components/layout/`
- Feature-specific components stay co-located: `/features/<feature-name>/components/`
- Never put business logic or API calls inside UI components — keep them dumb

## When to Create a Shared Component
- Only abstract into `/components/ui/` when a pattern appears 2+ times across different features
- On first use, build it locally in the feature folder
- On second use in a different feature, move it to shared

## Component Rules
- UI components receive all data via props — no direct API calls, no zustand/context reads
- Use TypeScript interfaces for all props, defined in the same file
- Export a single default component per file
- Keep components focused: if a component has more than ~150 lines, consider splitting

## File Naming
- Components: PascalCase (`UserCard.tsx`)
- Hooks: camelCase with `use` prefix (`useUserData.ts`)
- Utils: camelCase (`formatDate.ts`)
- Feature folders: kebab-case (`user-profile/`)

## Folder Structure
src/
  app/                  # Next.js app router pages
  components/
    ui/                 # Shared primitives (Button, Input, etc.)
    layout/             # Shared layout components
  features/
    <feature>/
      components/       # Feature-specific UI
      hooks/            # Feature-specific hooks
      utils/            # Feature-specific helpers
      types.ts          # Feature types
  hooks/                # Shared hooks
  lib/                  # Shared utilities, API clients
  types/                # Global types

## General
- Prefer composition over configuration — small focused components over one mega-flexible one
- Co-locate related files: a component, its hook, and its types can live together
- Avoid prop drilling more than 2 levels — use context or lift state